    en: "Court fines, fees, and surcharges can add up to hundreds or thousands of dollars after a conviction in New York. A person who cannot afford to pay can request a payment plan, ask for community service instead of payment, or ask the court to reduce the fine based on financial hardship. Under the U.S. Supreme Court's Bearden v. Georgia rule, a court cannot jail a person solely because the person is unable to pay. Penal Law 60.35 sets the mandatory surcharges. Failure to appear at a payment hearing, though, can lead to a warrant — so ignoring a notice is risky. Veterans with a service-connected condition may qualify for Veterans Treatment Court, which can reduce or dismiss fines on completion of the program."
